		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2017"></a><br><code>sle2017/paper15</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2017</a> paper:</span><br><i>Concurrent circular reference attribute grammars</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/JesperÖqvist.html">Jesper Öqvist</a>, <a href="../profile/GörelHedin.html">Görel Hedin</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3136014.3136032">10.1145/3136014.3136032</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagM">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> It focuses on concurrent evaluation of circular reference attribute grammars, i.e., runtime interpretation/execution of semantic specifications.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Reference attribute grammars are the underlying meta-language/formalism whose execution is optimized.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s motivation and results revolve around latency/throughput improvements via concurrency.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> Attribute-grammar evaluation computes static semantic information, and concurrency changes how that semantic computation is executed.
</li></ul></li></ul>
